element.label: protein substrate and ligand constant
element.description: They are used to express the binding interactions between labeled or unlabeled ligands with protein receptors and include Bmax, Kd, etc.

element.label: binding constant
element.description: This endpoint type describes the bonding affinity between two molecules at equilibrium, e.g., drug-receptor interaction.

element.label: Bmax
element.description: It is the amount of drug required to saturate a population of receptors and a measure of the number of receptors present in the sample. It is derived from Scatchard plot of binding data. It is analogous to Vmax in enzyme kinetics. The units of Bmax include cpm, sites/cell or fmol/mg. http://graphpad.com/curvefit/fitting_specific_binding_.htm

element.label: Kd
element.description: Kd ? is the equilibrium dissociation constant for a drug. It describes the affinity between a ligand (L) (such as a drug) and a protein (P). Ligand-protein affinities are influenced by non-covalent intermolecular interactions between the two molecules such as hydrogen bonding, electrostatic interactions, hydrophobic and Van der Waals forces. Kd = ([P] [L]) / [PL] The dissociation constant has molar units (M), which corresponds to the concentration of ligand [L] at which the binding site on a particular protein is half occupied, i.e. the concentration of ligand, at which the concentration of protein with ligand bound [PL], equals the concentration of protein with no ligand bound [P]. The smaller the dissociation constant, the more tightly bound the ligand is, or the higher the affinity between ligand and protein. http://www.graphpad.com/curvefit/law_of_mass_action.htm

element.label: Ki
element.description: Ki is the equilibrium inhibitor dissociation constant, the concentration of the competing inhibitor that results in binding to half the enzymes sites at equilibrium in the absence of substrate or other competitors. The Cheng and Prusoff equation: Ki - (IC50) / ( 1+ ([L]/Kd)) relates IC50 to Ki under conditions of competitive binding; Kd equilibrium dissociation constant of the (labeled) ligand, [L] ligand concentration. The Cheng and Prusoff equation: Ki - (IC50) / ( 1+ ([S]/Km)) relates IC50 to Ki under conditions of competitive inhibition; Ki equilibrium enzyme inhibitor dissociation constant; Km Michaelis-Menton constant, [S] substrate concentration.

element.label: enzyme kinetic constant
element.description: Describe kinetics of enzyme-catalyzed reactions. It includes the enzyme kinetic constants namely, Km and Vmax, which help to model the time course of disappearance of substrate and the production of product.

element.label: Vmax
element.description: Vmax is defined as the maximum initial velocity of an enzyme catalyzed reaction under the given conditions, and it is measured in units of quantity of substrate transformed per unit time for a given concentration of enzyme.

element.label: km
element.description: The concentration of substrate at ? Vmax, according to the Henri-Michaelis-Menten kinetic model.

element.label: koff
element.description: The off-rate associated with the release of inhibitor from an enzyme-inhibitor complex.

element.label: kon
element.description: The on-rate associated with the formation of an enzyme-inhibitor complex.

element.label: kcat
element.description: Turnover number representing the maximum number of substrate molecules converted to products per active site per unit time.

element.label: temperature endpoint
element.description: The types of endpoints that report changes in temperature as a measure of a biological reaction, e.g. tm.

element.label: Tm
element.description: Tm is defined as the midpoint temperatuere of the protein unfolding transition. It is determined by generating a thermal denaturation curve for the target molecule and taking the midpoint temperature between folding and unfolding state of the protein. In nucleic acid thermodynamics, it is the temperature at which 50% of the DNA strands and its perfect complement are in duplex.

element.label: time endpoint
element.description: An endpoint defined by a length in time at which a desired effect or observation occurs.

element.label: T1/2
element.description: An endpoint expressiong half-life.

element.label: dosage endpoint
element.description: An endpoint defined an effect seen in animals at a particular dosage, typically defined as a ratio of treatment to animal mass (e.g., mg/kg).

element.label: graphical calculation endpoint
element.description: An endpoint derived from calculus-based analysis of graphical measures.

element.label: cMax
element.description: A maximal concentration achieved in a dosing experiment (maximum point of a concentration curve).

element.label: area under curve
element.description: Area (e.g., integral) under a curve.

element.label: amplification curve calculated endpoint
element.description: Endpoint values derived from an exponential growth curve, such as in a PCR reaction.

element.label: Cp
element.description: Crossing point- In an exponential amplification curve (i.e., qPCR amplification) the value in number of amplification cycles at which the signal enters log phase, as determined by the maximal second derivative of the curve.

element.label: Cq
element.description: Quantificatoin cycle; general term, whether defined by Cp or Ct, for the value of interest determined from an exponential amplification curve (such as number of cycles in a PCR reaction).

element.label: Ct
element.description: Crossing threshold; in an exponential amplification curve (i.e., qPCR amplification) the value in number of amplification cycles at which the signal crosses a defined threshold.

element.label: physical property endpoint
element.description: A measurement of an intrinsic property of a molecular entity.

element.label: profile endpoint
element.description: An endpoint defined by a set of measurements from a multiparametric assay. The set of measurements may be aggregated to an overall profile score, weighting each measurment in the profile relative to a desired outcome.

element.label: concentration endpoint
element.description: It can refer to the screening concentration (for example in a primary assay) or it can be a concentration at which the perturbagen mediates a defined response, such as IC50 or EC50. It always has one value and a concentration unit.

element.label: CC50
element.description: The effective concentration of a cytotoxic compound, which produces 50% of the maximum possible cell death for that compound. Although the cytotoxic compound induces cell death, we define CC50 as subclass of IC50, because critical cellular processes are inhibited and CC50 is often used as a more specific description of IC50 for cell toxicity assays. Compound cytotoxicity is an important parameter to measure when developing potential human therapeutics. Cytotoxicity can be determined for example as a measure of radioisotope (3H thymidine or 51Cr) release, lactate dehydrogenase release from damaged cells, tetrazolium salt and alamar blue reduction, fluorescent dyes that selectively stain live or dead cells, or decrease in ATP content. ATP levels are detected using a luminescence based assay kit such as CellTiter-Glo (Promega). ATP values higher than controls (untreated cells) indicate proliferation and cultures with ATP concentrations lower than controls indicate cytotoxicity.

element.label: EC30
element.description: The effective concentration of an agonist, which produces 30% of the maximum possible response for that agonist.

element.label: LC50
element.description: 50% cell kill or lethal concentration ( the concentration that kills 50% of treated cells).

element.label: AC50
element.description: The effective concentration of a perturbagen, which produces 50% of the maximal possible response, which could mean either activation (EC50) or inhibition (IC50) for that perturbagen.

element.label: EC50
element.description: The effective concentration of an agonist, which produces 50% of the maximum possible response for that agonist.

element.label: IC50
element.description: The effective concentration of an inhibitor, which produces 50% of the maximum possible response for that inhibitor.

element.label: GI50
element.description: The effective concentration of a growth inhibitor, which produces 50% of the maximum possible response for that inhibitor. GI50 is calculated from [(Ti-Tz)/(C-Tz)] x 100 = 50, where Tz is absorbance at time zero, Ti is absorbance in the presence of test drug, and C is absorbance in the control (untreated cells). As a measure of viable or proliferating cells, different researchers measure different parameters, namely, protein content (by sulforhodamine B staining followed by absorbance measurement), mitochondrial dehydrogenase activity (by 3-(4,5-dimethylthiazol-2-yl)-2,5-diphenyl tetrasodium bromide, known as MTT staining followed by absorbance measurement), expression of proliferation associated antigens (by immunostaining for Ki-67), and ATP content (by using CellTiter-Glo reagent (Promega) followed by luminescence measurement).

element.label: IC50 absolute
element.description: Absolute IC50 (calculated from the curve-fit function) is the concentration corresponding to exactly 50 percent inhibition. It is obtained from the curve fit function (back-calculated IC50) and can also be extrapolated. Commonly the relative IC50 is reported; however in cell proliferation assays absolute IC50 is often used. The absolute IC50 can be more reproducible.

element.label: IC50 relative
element.description: The concentration of a test substance that produces an inhibitory effect corresponding to 50% of the activity of that particular substance (i.e. 50% of the difference between top and bottom of fitted curve). It can also be described as the concentration corresponding to the inflection point of the curve.

element.label: pIC50
element.description: pIC50 is -logIC50, where IC50 is the effective concentration of an inhibitor, which produces 50% of the maximum possible response for that inhibitor.

element.label: IC80
element.description: The effective concentration of an inhibitor, which produces 80% of the maximum possible response for that inhibitor.

element.label: TGI
element.description: TGI is total growth inhibition, which is the effective concentration of a growth inhibitor, which produces 0% relative growth for that inhibitor. Thus TGI signifies a cytostatic effect. tgi is calculated from [(Ti-Tz)/(C-Tz)] x 100 =0, where Ti = Tz and Tz is absorbance at time zero, Ti is absorbance in the presence of test drug, and C is absorbance in the control (untreated cells). As a measure of viable cells, different researchers measure different parameters, namely, protein content (by sulforhodamine B staining followed by absorbance measurement), mitochondrial dehydrogenase activity (by 3-(4,5-dimethylthiazol-2-yl)-2,5-diphenyl tetrasodium bromide, known as MTT staining followed by absorbance measurement), and ATP content (by using CellTiter-Glo reagent (Promega) followed by luminescence measurement).

element.label: screening concentration
element.description: The concentration of the perturbagen used in the assay to elicit the biological effect or perturbation.

element.label: response endpoint
element.description: Reporting the extent / magnitude of the perturbation (induced by the perturbagen) such as percent inhibition. Response-type endpoints would typically be obtained from a single concentration perturbagen measurement.

element.label: raw activity
element.description: Raw or qualitative data are reported as endpoints in an assay, e.g., luminescence counts, fluorescence intensity, etc.

element.label: statistical endpoint
element.description: Endpoint values determined by a statistical measurement of the signal relative to the populations of signals observed.

element.label: MAD score
element.description: The number of median absolute deviations outside the median of control or compound wells.

element.label: B-score
element.description: The B score is an analog of the Z score, but is more resistant to the presence of outliers and to differences in the measurement error distributions of the compounds. It is calculated by first computing a two-way median to account for row and column effects of the plate, which is then divided by their median absolute deviation to standardize for plate-to-plate variability.

element.label: Z-score
element.description: Random and systematic error can induce either underestimation (false negatives) or overestimation (false positives) of measured signals. Z score indicates how many standard deviations an observation is above or below the mean. For calculating this, the average of the plate values is subtracted from individual raw values and the difference divided by the standard deviation estimated from all measurements of the plate.

element.label: percent response
element.description: Percent increase or decrease of a predefined stimulus. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay.

element.label: efficacy
element.description: The maximum response that can be achieved with the perturbagen as percentage of the positive control.

element.label: maximal inhibition
element.description: Maximum inhibition of an antagonist or inhibitor (relative an efficacious positive control)

element.label: maximal activation
element.description: The maximum percent activation of an agonist

element.label: percent activity
element.description: Percent activity is the response relative to an unperturbed state; in case of inhibition the interpretation is that of remaining activity, i.e. percent inhibition := 100 - percent activity.

element.label: percent viability
element.description: It is a measure of living cells in a culture well. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay. It can be estimated in the compound treated wells in comparison to vehicle-treated control wells and is expressed as a percent. Viability is determined by measuring tetrazolium salt and alamar blue reduction, staining with selective fluorescent dyes, or ATP content. ATP levels are detected using a luminescence based assay kit such as CellTiter-Glo (Promega). ATP values higher than controls indicate proliferation and cultures with ATP concentrations lower than controls indicates cytotoxicity. Percent viability = 100-percent cytotoxicity

element.label: 50 percent viability
element.description: Assay has 50% living cells. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay.

element.label: percent activation
element.description: Percent increase of a measureable response relative to some baseline. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay. Percent activity measures the increased activity vs. an unperturbed state, i.e. percent activation := percent activity - 100; e.g. an agonist that results in twice the activity would have percent activity = 200 and percent activation = 100.

element.label: 50 percent activation
element.description: 50% increase of a predefined stimulus. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay.

element.label: percent inhibition
element.description: Percent decrease of a measureable response as a consequence of compound treatment. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay. Percent inhibition is expressed relative to a positive control (which results in total inhibition).

element.label: percent growth inhibition
element.description: % growth reduction of a predefined stimulus. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay.

element.label: 50 percent inhibition
element.description: 50% reduction of a predefined stimulus. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay.

element.label: 80 percent inhibition
element.description: 80% reduction of a predefined stimulus. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay.

element.label: fold change
element.description: It is the ratio of biological activity in the presence of an exogenous substance to that in its absence. The fold change is useful when comparing test compounds evaluated across multiple functional assays because varying levels of efficacy can be observed amongst the different or same reference agonists.

element.label: fold activation
element.description: The ratio of biological activity in the presence of an exogenous substance to that in its absence. This result type is used exclusively with single point (screening concentration) assays.

element.label: fold inhibition
element.description: The ratio of biological activity in the absence of an exogenous substance to that in its presence. This result type is used exclusively with single point (screening concentration) assays.

element.label: FOC
element.description: Fold of control

element.label: microsecond
element.description: A time unit which is equal to one millionth of a second or 10^[-6] s.

element.label: picosecond

element.description: An electric current unit current which is equal to one thousandth of an ampere or 10^[-3] A.

element.label: microampere
element.description: An electric current unit current which is equal to one millionth of an ampere or 10^[-6] A.

element.label: temperature unit

element.label: picomole

element.label: femtomole
element.description: A substance unit equal to 10^[-15] mol.

element.label: attomole

element.label: candela

element.label: micromolar

element.label: nanomolar
element.description: A unit of molarity which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a molar or 10^[-9] M.

element.label: picomolar
element.description: A unit of molarity which is equal to 10^[-12] M.

element.label: femtomolar
element.description: A unit of molarity which is equal to 10^[-15] M.

element.label: unit of molality
element.description: A derived concentration unit which is a standard measure of the number of moles of a given substance per kilogram of solvent.

element.label: molal
element.description: A unit of concentration which expresses a concentration of a solution of 1 mole per kilogram of solvent (mol/kg).

element.label: millimolal
element.description: A molality unit which is equal to one thousandth of a molal or 10^[-3] m.

element.label: micromolal
element.description: A molality unit which is equal to one millionth of a molal or 10^[-6] m.

element.label: nanomolal
element.description: A molality unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a molal or 10^[-9] m.

element.label: picomolal
element.description: A molality unit which is equal to 10^[-12] m.

element.description: A unit of concentration which highlights the chemical nature of salts.

element.label: unit per volume unit
element.description: A derived concentration unit which is a standard measure of the number of units, as an agreed arbitrary amount, of a given substance per a specific volume of solution.

element.description: A unit per milliliter unit which is equal to one unit of an agreed arbitrary amount per one milliliter.

element.label: unit per liter
element.description: A unit per milliliter unit which is equal to one unit of an agreed arbitrary amount per one liter.

element.label: gram per cubic centimeter
element.description: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in cubic centimeters.

element.label: gram per milliliter
element.description: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in milliliter.

element.label: kilogram per liter
element.description: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in kilograms divided by the volume in liters.

element.label: gram per liter
element.description: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in liters.

element.label: milligram per milliliter
element.description: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in milligrams divided by the volume in milliliters.

element.label: gram per deciliter
element.description: A mass density unit which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in deciliters.

element.label: microgram per liter
element.description: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in micrograms divided by the volume in liters.

element.label: cell concentration unit

element.label: cells per milliliter

element.description: A volume per unit volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter of solute in one cubic meter of solution.

element.label: milliliter per liter
element.description: A volume per unit volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter of solute in one liter of solution.

element.label: colony forming unit per volume

element.description: A molar mass unit which is equal to one gram of mass of one mole of chemical element or chemical compound.

element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the volume of a homogeneous substance containing 6.02 x 1023 atoms or molecules.

element.label: cubic centimeter per mole
element.description: A molar volume unit which is equal to 1 cubic centimeter occupied by one mole of a substance in the form of a solid, liquid, or gas.

element.label: momentum unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the quantity of motion measured by the product of mass and velocity.

element.label: rotational frequency unit

element.label: one turn per second

element.label: specific volume unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the volume of a given mass of substance (the reciprocal of density).

element.label: cubic meter per kilogram
element.description: A specific volume unit which is equal to one cubic meter volume occupied by one kilogram of a particular substance.

element.label: liter per kilogram
element.description: A specific volume unit which is equal to one liter volume occupied by one kilogram of a particular substance.

element.description: A specific volume unit which is equal to a thousandth of a liter per kilogram or 10^[-3] l/kg.

element.label: microliter per kilogram
element.description: A specific volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter per kilogram or 10^[-6] l/kg.

element.description: A volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a cubic meter or 10^[-9] m^[3], or to 1 ml.

element.label: milliliter
element.description: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of a liter or 10^[-3] L, or to 1 cubic centimeter.

element.label: liter
element.description: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of a cubic meter or 10^[-3] m^[3], or to 1 decimeter.

element.label: cubic decimeter
element.description: A volume unit which is equal to one thousand of a cubic meter or 10^[-3] m^[3], or to 1 L.

element.label: microliter
element.description: A volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter or 10^[-6] L.

element.label: nanoliter
element.description: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a liter or 10^[-9] L.

element.label: picoliter
element.description: A volume unit which is equal to 10^[-12] L.

element.label: femtoliter
element.description: A volume unit which is equal to 10^[-15] L.

element.label: deciliter
element.description: A volume unit which is equal to one tenth of a liter or 10^[-1] L.

element.label: frequency unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the number of repetitive actions in a particular time.

element.label: hertz
element.description: A frequency unit which is equal to 1 complete cycle of a recurring phenomenon in 1 second.

element.label: force unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the force is applied when a mass is accelerated.

element.label: newton
element.description: A force unit which is equal to the force required to cause an acceleration of 1m/s2 of a mass of 1 Kg in the direction of the force.

element.label: pressure unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the force applied to a given area.

element.label: pascal
element.description: A pressure unit which is equal to the pressure or stress on a surface caused by a force of 1 newton spread over a surface of 1 m^[2].

element.label: millimetres of mercury
element.description: A unit of pressure equal to the amount of fluid pressure one millimeter deep in mercury at zero degrees centigrade on Earth.

element.label: energy unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the work done by a certain force (gravitational, electric, magnetic, force of inertia, etc).

element.label: joule
element.description: An energy unit which is equal to the energy required when a force of 1 newton moves an object 1 meter in the direction of the force.

element.label: watt-hour
element.description: An energy unit which is equal to the amount of electrical energy equivalent to a one-watt load drawing power for one hour.

element.label: kilowatt-hour
element.description: An energy unit which is equal to 1,000 watt-hours.

element.label: electronvolt
element.description: A non-SI unit of energy (eV) defined as the energy acquired by a single unbound electron when it passes through an electrostatic potential difference of one volt. An electronvolt is equal to 1.602 176 53(14) x 10^-19 J.

element.label: power unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure power or the rate of doing work.

element.label: watt
element.description: A power unit which is equal to the power used when work is done at the rate of 1 joule per second.

element.label: catalytic activity unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the amount of the action of a catalyst.

element.label: katal
element.description: A catalytic unit activity which is equal to the activity of a catalyst in moles per second, such as the amount of an enzyme needed to transform one mole of substrate per second.

element.label: enzyme unit
element.description: A catalytic unit activity which is equal to the amount of the enzyme that catalyzes the conversion of 1 micro mole of substrate per minute.

element.label: angle unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the figure or space formed by the junction of two lines or planes.

element.label: plane angle unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the angle formed by two straight lines in the same plane.

element.label: radian
element.description: A plane angle unit which is equal to the angle subtended at the center of a circle by an arc equal in length to the radius of the circle, approximately 57 degrees 17 minutes and 44.6 seconds.

element.label: degree
element.description: A plane angle unit which is equal to 1/360 of a full rotation or 1.7453310^[-2] rad.

element.label: solid angle unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the angle formed by three or more planes intersecting at a common point.

element.label: steradian
element.description: A solid angle unit which is equal to the solid angle subtended at the center of a sphere by an area on the surface of the sphere that is equal to the radius squared.

element.label: temperature derived unit
element.description: A derived unit which represents a standard measurement of temperature in a particular temperature scale.

element.label: degree celsius
element.description: A temperature derived unit which is equal to one Kelvin degree. However, they have their zeros at different points. The Centigrade scale has its zero at 273.15 K.

element.label: degree fahrenheit
element.description: A temperature derived unit which is equal to 5/9ths of a kelvin. Negative 40 degrees Fahrenheit is equal to negative 40 degrees Celsius.

element.label: radiation unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the amount of radiation emitted by a given radiation source as well as the amount of radiation absorbed or deposited in a specific material by a radiation source.

element.label: activity (of a radionuclide) unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the transformation (disintegration) rate of a radioactive substance.

element.label: becquerel
element.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second or there is one atom disintegration per second (dps).

element.label: curie
element.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which there are 3.7 x 10^[10] atom disintegration per second (dps).

element.label: millicurie
element.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to one thousandth of a curie or 10^[-3] Ci.

element.label: microcurie
element.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to one millionth of a curie or 10^[-6] Ci.

element.label: disintegrations per minute
element.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per minute or there is one atom disintegration per minute.

element.label: counts per minute
element.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the number of light emissions produced by ionizing radiation in one minute.

element.label: disintegrations per second
element.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second or there is one atom disintegration per second.

element.label: absorbed dose unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the energy imparted by ionizing radiation to unit mass of matter such as tissue.

element.label: gray
element.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to the absorption of one joule of radiation energy by one kilogram of matter.

element.label: rad
element.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to 0.01 gray (Gy).

element.label: microgray
element.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one millionth of a gray or 10^[-6] Gy.

element.label: milligray
element.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one thousandth of a gray or 10^[-3] Gy.

element.label: nanogray
element.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one thousandth of a millionth of a gray or 10^[-9] Gy.

element.label: dose equivalent unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the expression of dose in terms of its biological effect.

element.label: sievert
element.description: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to the absorption of one joule of radiation energy by one kilogram of matter.

element.label: millisievert
element.description: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one thousandth of a sievert or 10^[-3] Sv.

element.label: microsievert
element.description: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one millionth of a sievert or 10^[-6] Sv.

element.label: Roentgen equivalent man
element.description: A dose equivalent unit which when multiplied by hundred is equal to one sievert or 1 Sv. 1 Sv is equal to 100 rem.

element.label: nanosievert
element.description: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one thousandth of a millionth of a sievert or 10^[-9] Sv.

element.label: exposure unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the quantity that expresses the ability of radiation to ionize air and thereby create electric charges which can be collected and measured.

element.label: roentgen
element.description: An exposure unit which is equal to the amount of radiation required to liberate positive and negative charges of one electrostatic unit of charge in 1 cm^[3] of air at standard temperature and pressure (STP). This corresponds to the generation of approximately 2.0810^[9] ion pairs.

element.label: effective dose unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the estimate of the stochastic effect that a non-uniform radiation dose has on a human.

element.label: time derived unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the dimension in which events occur in sequence.

element.label: century
element.description: A time unit which is equal to 100 years.

element.label: half life
element.description: A time unit which represents the period over which the activity or concentration of a specified chemical or element falls to half its original activity or concentration.

element.label: minute
element.description: A time unit which is equal to 60 seconds.

element.label: hour
element.description: A time unit which is equal to 3600 seconds or 60 minutes.

element.label: day
element.description: A time unit which is equal to 24 hours.

element.label: week
element.description: A time unit which is equal to 7 days.

element.label: year
element.description: A time unit which is equal to 12 months which is science is taken to be equal to 365.25 days.

element.label: light unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the intensity of light.

element.label: luminance unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the luminous intensity impinging on a given area.

element.label: candela per square meter
element.description: A luminance unit which is equal to a luminous intensity of one candela radiating from a surface whose area is one square meter.

element.label: illuminance unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the luminous flux incident on a unit area.

element.label: lux
element.description: An illuminance unit which is equal to the illuminance produced by 1 lumen evenly spread over an area 1 m^[2].

element.label: foot candle
element.description: An illuminance unit which is equal to the illuminance produced by 1 lumen evenly spread over an area 1 foot^[2]. One footcandle is equal to 10.76 lux.

element.label: luminous flux unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the flow of radiant energy.

element.label: lumen
element.description: A luminous flux unit which is equal to the luminous flux emitted into 1 steradian by a point source of 1 candela.

element.label: irradiance unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the power of electromagnetic radiation at a surface, per unit area.

element.label: watt per square meter
element.description: An irradiance unit which is equal to 1 watt of radiant power incident per one square meter surface area.

element.label: microeinstein per square meter per second
element.description: An irradiance unit which is equal to one microeinstein per square meter per second or 10^[-6] microeinstein/sm^[2].

element.label: radiant intensity unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the intensity of electromagnetic radiation.

element.label: watt per steradian
element.description: A radiant intensity unit which is equal to one kilogram meter squared per second cubed per steradian.

element.label: radiance unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the power of electromagnetic radiation through space or through a material medium in the form of electromagnetic waves.

element.label: watt per steradian per square meter
element.description: A radiance unit which is equal to one watt of radiant power incident per steradian solid angle per one square meter projected area of the source, as viewed from the given direction.

element.label: area unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the amount of a 2-dimensional flat surface.

element.label: square meter
element.description: An area unit which is equal to an area enclosed by a square with sides each 1 meter long.

element.label: square centimeter
element.description: An area unit which is equal to one thousand of square meter or 10^[-3] m^[2].

element.label: square millimeter
element.description: An area unit which is equal to one millionth of a square meter or 10^[-6] m^[2].

element.label: acceleration unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the rate of change of velocity in either speed or direction.

element.label: meter per second per second
element.description: An acceleration unit which is equal to the acceleration an object changing its velocity by 1meter/s over a time period that equals one second.

element.label: angular velocity unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the rate of angular movement about an axis; the angle rotated in a given time.

element.label: radian per second
element.description: An angular unit velocity which is equal to about 9.54930 rpm (revolutions per minute).

element.label: density unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the influence exerted by some mass.

element.label: mass density unit
element.description: A density unit which is a standard measure of the mass of a substance in a given volume.

element.label: area density unit
element.description: A density unit which is a standard measure of the mass exerting an influence on a given area.

element.label: kilogram per square meter
element.description: An area density unit which is equal to the mass of an object in kilograms divided by the surface area in meters squared.

element.label: linear density unit
element.description: A density unit which is a standard measure of the mass exerting an influence on a one-dimensional object.

element.label: kilogram per meter
element.description: An area density unit which is equal to the mass of an object in kilograms divided by one meter.

element.label: dimensionless unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of physical quantity consisting of only a numerical number without any units.

element.label: parts per notation
element.description: A dimensionless concentration notation which describes the amount of one substance in another. It is the ratio of the amount of the substance of interest to the amount of that substance plus the amount of the substance.

element.label: parts per hundred
element.description: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 100 regardless of the units of measure as long as they are the same.

element.label: parts per thousand
element.description: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1000 regardless of the units of measure as long as they are the same.

element.label: parts per million
element.description: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000 regardless of the units of measure used as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[6].

element.label: parts per billion
element.description: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000,000 regardless of the units of measure as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[9].

element.label: parts per trillion
element.description: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000,000 regardless of the units of measure used as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[12].

element.label: parts per quadrillion
element.description: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000,000,000 regardless of the units of measure used as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[15].

element.label: count unit
element.description: A dimensionless unit which denotes a simple count of things.

element.label: molecule count
element.description: A dimensionless count unit which denotes the number of molecules.

element.label: colony forming unit
element.description: A dimensionless count unit which a measure of viable bacterial numbers.

element.label: plaque forming unit
element.description: A dimensionless count unit which a measure of plague forming units in a given volume.

element.label: base pair
element.description: A count unit which contains one nucleotide.

element.label: ratio unit
element.description: A dimensionless unit which denotes an amount or magnitude of one quantity relative to another.

element.label: percent
element.description: A dimensionless ratio unit which denotes numbers as fractions of 100.

element.label: mass volume percentage
element.description: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the mass of the substance in a mixture as a percentage of the volume of the entire mixture.

element.label: purity percentage
element.description: A dimensionless percent unit which denotes the homogeneity of a biomaterial.

element.label: confluence percentage
element.description: A dimensionless percent unit which denotes the density of an attached or monolayer culture (e.g., cell culture).

element.label: mass percentage
element.description: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the mass of a substance in a mixture as a percentage of the mass of the entire mixture.

element.label: fraction
element.description: A dimensionless ratio unit which relates the part (the numerator) to the whole (the denominator).

element.label: mole fraction
element.description: A concentration unit which denotes the number of moles of solute as a proportion of the total number of moles in a solution.

element.label: decibel
element.description: An ratio unit which is an indicator of sound power per unit area.

element.label: pH
element.description: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the acidity of a solution in terms of activity of hydrogen ions (H+).

element.label: absorbance unit
element.description: A dimensionless logarithmic unit assigned to a measure of absorbance of light through a partially absorbing substance, defined as -log10(I/I_0) where I = transmitted light and I_0 = incident light.

element.label: electric potential difference
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the work done per unit charge as a charge is moved between two points in an electric field.

element.label: volt
element.description: An electric potential difference unit which is equal to the work per unit charge. One volt is the potential difference required to move one coulomb of charge between two points in a circuit while using one joule of energy.

element.label: millivolt
element.description: An electric potential difference unit which is equal to one thousandth of a volt or 10^[-3] V.

element.label: kilovolt
element.description: An electric potential difference unit which is equal to one thousand volts or 10^[3] V.

element.label: microvolt
element.description: An electric potential difference unit which is equal to one millionth of a volt or 10^[-6] V.

element.label: nanovolt
element.description: An electric potential difference unit which is equal to one billionth of a volt or 10^[-12] V.

element.label: picovolt
element.description: An electric potential difference unit which is equal to one trillionth of a volt or 10^[-12] V.

element.label: megavolt
element.description: An electric potential difference unit which is equal to one million volts or 10^[6] V.

element.label: electric charge
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the quantity of unbalanced electricity in a body (either positive or negative) and construed as an excess or deficiency of electrons.

element.label: coulomb
element.description: An electrical charge unit which is equal to the amount of charge transferred by a current of 1 ampere in 1 second.

element.label: magnetic flux unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of quantity of magnetism, taking account of the strength and the extent of a magnetic field.

element.label: weber
element.description: A magnetic flux unit which is equal to the amount of flux that when linked with a single turn of wire for an interval of one second will induce an electromotive force of one volt.

element.label: volt-hour
element.description: A magnetic flux unit which is equal to 3600 Wb.

element.label: kilovolt-hour
element.description: A magnetic flux unit which is equal to one thousand volt-hours.

element.label: magnetic flux density unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the strength of a magnetic field.

element.label: tesla
element.description: A magnetic flux density unit which is equal to one weber per square meter.

element.label: information unit
element.description: A unit which is a standard measure of the amount of information.

element.label: bit
element.description: An information unit which refers to a digit in the binary numeral system, which consists of base 2 digits (ie there are only 2 possible values

element.label: byte
element.description: An information unit which is equal to 8 bits.

element.label: kilobyte
element.description: An information unit which is equal to 1000 bytes.

element.label: megabyte
element.description: An information unit which is equal to 1000 kB.

element.label: image resolution unit
element.description: An information unit which is a standard measure of the detail an image holds.

element.label: chroma sampling unit
element.description: An image resolution unit which is a standard measure of the amount of spatial detail in an image.

element.label: dynamic range unit
element.description: An image resolution unit which is a standard measure of the amount of contrast available in a pixel.

element.label: spatial resolution unit
element.description: An image resolution unit which is a standard measure of the way luminance and chrominance may be sampled at different levels.

element.label: dots per inch
element.description: A spatial resolution unit which is a standard measure of the printing resolution, in particular the number of individual dots of ink a printer or toner can produce within a linear one-inch space.

element.label: micron pixel
element.description: A spatial resolution unit which is equal to a pixel size of one micrometer.

element.label: pixels per inch
element.description: A spatial resolution unit which is a standard measure of the resolution of a computer display, related to the size of the display in inches and the total number of pixels in the horizontal and vertical directions.

element.label: pixels per millimeter
element.description: A spatial resolution unit which is a standard measure of the number of pixels in one millimeter length or width of a digital image divided by the physical length or width of a printed image.

element.label: kibibyte
element.description: An information unit which is equal to 1024 B.

element.label: mebibyte
element.description: An information unit which is equal to 1024 KiB.

element.label: surface tension unit
element.description: A unit which is a standard measure of the ability of a liguid to attraction of molecules at its surface as a result of unbalanced molecular cohesive forces.

element.label: newton per meter
element.description: A surface tension unit which is equal to one newton per meter.

element.label: dyne per cm
element.description: A surface tension unit which is equal to one dyne per centimeter.

element.label: viscosity unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the internal resistance of fluids to flow.

element.label: pascal second
element.description: A viscosity unit which is equal to one pascale per second.

element.label: poise
element.description: A viscosity unit which is equal to one dyne second per square centimeter.

element.label: conduction unit
element.description: A derived unit which represents a standard measurement of the transmission of an entity through a medium.

element.label: electrical conduction unit
element.description: A derived unit which represents a standard measurement of the movement of electrically charged particles through a transmission medium (electrical conductor).

element.label: siemens
element.description: An electrical conduction unit which is equal to A/V.

element.label: heat conduction unit
element.description: A derived unit which represents a standard measurement of the spontaneous transfer of thermal energy through matter, from a region of higher temperature to a region of lower temperature.

element.label: watt per meter kelvin
element.description: An heat conduction unit which is equal to one watt divided by meter kelvin.

element.label: electric field strength unit
element.description: The electric field strength is a derived unit which is a measure of the potential difference between two points some distance apart.

element.label: volt per meter
element.description: The volt per meter is a unit of electric field strength equal to the a potential difference of 1 volt existing between two points that are 1 meter apart.

element.label: volumetric flow rate unit
element.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the volume of fluid which passes through a given surface per unit time .

element.label: microliters per minute
element.description: A volumetric flow rate unit which is equal to one microliter volume through a given surface in one minute.

They are used to express the binding interactions between labeled or unlabeled ligands with protein receptors and include Bmax, Kd, etc.
This endpoint type describes the bonding affinity between two molecules at equilibrium, e.g., drug-receptor interaction.

Kd ? is the equilibrium dissociation constant for a drug. It describes the affinity between a ligand (L) (such as a drug) and a protein (P). Ligand-protein affinities are influenced by non-covalent intermolecular interactions between the two molecules such as hydrogen bonding, electrostatic interactions, hydrophobic and Van der Waals forces. Kd = ([P] [L]) / [PL] The dissociation constant has molar units (M), which corresponds to the concentration of ligand [L] at which the binding site on a particular protein is half occupied, i.e. the concentration of ligand, at which the concentration of protein with ligand bound [PL], equals the concentration of protein with no ligand bound [P]. The smaller the dissociation constant, the more tightly bound the ligand is, or the higher the affinity between ligand and protein. http://www.graphpad.com/curvefit/law_of_mass_action.htm

Ki is the equilibrium inhibitor dissociation constant, the concentration of the competing inhibitor that results in binding to half the enzymes sites at equilibrium in the absence of substrate or other competitors. The Cheng and Prusoff equation: Ki - (IC50) / ( 1+ ([L]/Kd)) relates IC50 to Ki under conditions of competitive binding; Kd equilibrium dissociation constant of the (labeled) ligand, [L] ligand concentration. The Cheng and Prusoff equation: Ki - (IC50) / ( 1+ ([S]/Km)) relates IC50 to Ki under conditions of competitive inhibition; Ki equilibrium enzyme inhibitor dissociation constant; Km Michaelis-Menton constant, [S] substrate concentration.

It is the amount of drug required to saturate a population of receptors and a measure of the number of receptors present in the sample. It is derived from Scatchard plot of binding data. It is analogous to Vmax in enzyme kinetics. The units of Bmax include cpm, sites/cell or fmol/mg. http://graphpad.com/curvefit/fitting_specific_binding_.htm

Describe kinetics of enzyme-catalyzed reactions. It includes the enzyme kinetic constants namely, Km and Vmax, which help to model the time course of disappearance of substrate and the production of product.
The concentration of substrate at ? Vmax, according to the Henri-Michaelis-Menten kinetic model.
The off-rate associated with the release of inhibitor from an enzyme-inhibitor complex.

Vmax is defined as the maximum initial velocity of an enzyme catalyzed reaction under the given conditions, and it is measured in units of quantity of substrate transformed per unit time for a given concentration of enzyme.
The on-rate associated with the formation of an enzyme-inhibitor complex.
Turnover number representing the maximum number of substrate molecules converted to products per active site per unit time.
The types of endpoints that report changes in temperature as a measure of a biological reaction, e.g. tm.

Tm is defined as the midpoint temperatuere of the protein unfolding transition. It is determined by generating a thermal denaturation curve for the target molecule and taking the midpoint temperature between folding and unfolding state of the protein. In nucleic acid thermodynamics, it is the temperature at which 50% of the DNA strands and its perfect complement are in duplex.

TGI is total growth inhibition, which is the effective concentration of a growth inhibitor, which produces 0% relative growth for that inhibitor. Thus TGI signifies a cytostatic effect. tgi is calculated from [(Ti-Tz)/(C-Tz)] x 100 =0, where Ti = Tz and Tz is absorbance at time zero, Ti is absorbance in the presence of test drug, and C is absorbance in the control (untreated cells). As a measure of viable cells, different researchers measure different parameters, namely, protein content (by sulforhodamine B staining followed by absorbance measurement), mitochondrial dehydrogenase activity (by 3-(4,5-dimethylthiazol-2-yl)-2,5-diphenyl tetrasodium bromide, known as MTT staining followed by absorbance measurement), and ATP content (by using CellTiter-Glo reagent (Promega) followed by luminescence measurement).

The B score is an analog of the Z score, but is more resistant to the presence of outliers and to differences in the measurement error distributions of the compounds. It is calculated by first computing a two-way median to account for row and column effects of the plate, which is then divided by their median absolute deviation to standardize for plate-to-plate variability.

Random and systematic error can induce either underestimation (false negatives) or overestimation (false positives) of measured signals. Z score indicates how many standard deviations an observation is above or below the mean. For calculating this, the average of the plate values is subtracted from individual raw values and the difference divided by the standard deviation estimated from all measurements of the plate.

The effective concentration of a perturbagen, which produces 50% of the maximal possible response, which could mean either activation (EC50) or inhibition (IC50) for that perturbagen.

The effective concentration of a cytotoxic compound, which produces 50% of the maximum possible cell death for that compound. Although the cytotoxic compound induces cell death, we define CC50 as subclass of IC50, because critical cellular processes are inhibited and CC50 is often used as a more specific description of IC50 for cell toxicity assays. Compound cytotoxicity is an important parameter to measure when developing potential human therapeutics. Cytotoxicity can be determined for example as a measure of radioisotope (3H thymidine or 51Cr) release, lactate dehydrogenase release from damaged cells, tetrazolium salt and alamar blue reduction, fluorescent dyes that selectively stain live or dead cells, or decrease in ATP content. ATP levels are detected using a luminescence based assay kit such as CellTiter-Glo (Promega). ATP values higher than controls (untreated cells) indicate proliferation and cultures with ATP concentrations lower than controls indicate cytotoxicity.
The effective concentration of an agonist, which produces 30% of the maximum possible response for that agonist.
The effective concentration of an agonist, which produces 50% of the maximum possible response for that agonist.
The effective concentration of an inhibitor, which produces 50% of the maximum possible response for that inhibitor.

The effective concentration of a growth inhibitor, which produces 50% of the maximum possible response for that inhibitor. GI50 is calculated from [(Ti-Tz)/(C-Tz)] x 100 = 50, where Tz is absorbance at time zero, Ti is absorbance in the presence of test drug, and C is absorbance in the control (untreated cells). As a measure of viable or proliferating cells, different researchers measure different parameters, namely, protein content (by sulforhodamine B staining followed by absorbance measurement), mitochondrial dehydrogenase activity (by 3-(4,5-dimethylthiazol-2-yl)-2,5-diphenyl tetrasodium bromide, known as MTT staining followed by absorbance measurement), expression of proliferation associated antigens (by immunostaining for Ki-67), and ATP content (by using CellTiter-Glo reagent (Promega) followed by luminescence measurement).
pIC50 is -logIC50, where IC50 is the effective concentration of an inhibitor, which produces 50% of the maximum possible response for that inhibitor.

Absolute IC50 (calculated from the curve-fit function) is the concentration corresponding to exactly 50 percent inhibition. It is obtained from the curve fit function (back-calculated IC50) and can also be extrapolated. Commonly the relative IC50 is reported; however in cell proliferation assays absolute IC50 is often used. The absolute IC50 can be more reproducible.

The concentration of a test substance that produces an inhibitory effect corresponding to 50% of the activity of that particular substance (i.e. 50% of the difference between top and bottom of fitted curve). It can also be described as the concentration corresponding to the inflection point of the curve.
The effective concentration of an inhibitor, which produces 80% of the maximum possible response for that inhibitor.

descriptor.label: mass unit

descriptor.label: gram

descriptor.label: nanogram
descriptor.description: A mass unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a gram or 10^[-9] g.

descriptor.label: femtogram
descriptor.description: A mass unit which is equal to 10^[-15] g.

descriptor.label: kilogram
descriptor.description: A mass unit which is equal to the mass of the International Prototype Kilogram kept by the BIPM at Svres, France.

descriptor.label: milligram
descriptor.description: A mass unit which is equal to one thousandth of a gram or 10^[-3] g.

descriptor.label: microgram
descriptor.description: A mass unit which is equal to one millionth of a gram or 10^[-6] g.

descriptor.label: picogram
descriptor.description: A mass unit which is equal to 10^[-12] g.

descriptor.label: dalton
descriptor.description: An independently to the base SI units defined mass unit which is equal to one twelfth of the mass of an unbound atom of the carbon-12 nuclide, at rest and in its ground state.

descriptor.label: kilodalton
descriptor.description: A mass unit which is equal to one thousand daltons.

descriptor.label: electric current unit
descriptor.description: A base unit which is a standard measure of the flow of electric charge.

descriptor.label: milliampere
descriptor.description: An electric current unit current which is equal to one thousandth of an ampere or 10^[-3] A.

descriptor.label: ampere
descriptor.description: An electric current unit which is equal to the constant current which, if maintained in two straight parallel conductors of infinite length, of negligible circular cross-section, and placed 1 m apart in vacuum, would produce between these conductors a force equal to 2 x 10^[-7] newton per meter of length.

descriptor.label: microampere
descriptor.description: An electric current unit current which is equal to one millionth of an ampere or 10^[-6] A.

descriptor.label: temperature unit
descriptor.description: A base unit which is a standard measure of the average kinetic energy of the particles in a sample of matter.

descriptor.label: kelvin
descriptor.description: A thermodynamic temperature unit which is equal to the fraction 1/273.16 of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water.

descriptor.label: luminous intensity unit
descriptor.description: A base unit which is a standard measure of the wavelength-weighted power emitted by a light source in a particular direction.

descriptor.label: candela
descriptor.description: A luminous intensity unit which equal to the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540 x 1012 hertz and that has a radiant intensity in that direction of 1/683 watt per steradian.

descriptor.label: derived unit
descriptor.description: A unit which is derived from base units.

descriptor.label: angular acceleration unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the rate of change of angular velocity.

descriptor.label: radian per second per second
descriptor.description: An angular unit acceleration which is equal to the angular acceleration of an object changing its angular velocity by 1rad/s over a time period that equals one second.

descriptor.label: momentum unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the quantity of motion measured by the product of mass and velocity.

descriptor.label: kilogram meter per second
descriptor.description: A momentum unit which is equal to the momentum of a one kilogram mass object with a speed of one meter per second.

descriptor.label: specific volume unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the volume of a given mass of substance (the reciprocal of density).

descriptor.label: microliter per kilogram
descriptor.description: A specific volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter per kilogram or 10^[-6] l/kg.

descriptor.label: cubic meter per kilogram
descriptor.description: A specific volume unit which is equal to one cubic meter volume occupied by one kilogram of a particular substance.

descriptor.label: liter per kilogram
descriptor.description: A specific volume unit which is equal to one liter volume occupied by one kilogram of a particular substance.

descriptor.label: milliliter per kilogram
descriptor.description: A specific volume unit which is equal to a thousandth of a liter per kilogram or 10^[-3] l/kg.

descriptor.label: force unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the force is applied when a mass is accelerated.

descriptor.label: newton
descriptor.description: A force unit which is equal to the force required to cause an acceleration of 1m/s2 of a mass of 1 Kg in the direction of the force.

descriptor.label: energy unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the work done by a certain force (gravitational, electric, magnetic, force of inertia, etc).

descriptor.label: kilowatt-hour
descriptor.description: An energy unit which is equal to 1,000 watt-hours.

descriptor.label: joule
descriptor.description: An energy unit which is equal to the energy required when a force of 1 newton moves an object 1 meter in the direction of the force.

descriptor.label: watt-hour
descriptor.description: An energy unit which is equal to the amount of electrical energy equivalent to a one-watt load drawing power for one hour.

descriptor.label: electronvolt
descriptor.description: A non-SI unit of energy (eV) defined as the energy acquired by a single unbound electron when it passes through an electrostatic potential difference of one volt. An electronvolt is equal to 1.602 176 53(14) x 10^-19 J.

descriptor.label: power unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure power or the rate of doing work.

descriptor.label: watt
descriptor.description: A power unit which is equal to the power used when work is done at the rate of 1 joule per second.

descriptor.label: angle unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the figure or space formed by the junction of two lines or planes.

descriptor.label: plane angle unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the angle formed by two straight lines in the same plane.

descriptor.label: degree
descriptor.description: A plane angle unit which is equal to 1/360 of a full rotation or 1.7453310^[-2] rad.

descriptor.label: radian
descriptor.description: A plane angle unit which is equal to the angle subtended at the center of a circle by an arc equal in length to the radius of the circle, approximately 57 degrees 17 minutes and 44.6 seconds.

descriptor.label: solid angle unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the angle formed by three or more planes intersecting at a common point.

descriptor.label: steradian
descriptor.description: A solid angle unit which is equal to the solid angle subtended at the center of a sphere by an area on the surface of the sphere that is equal to the radius squared.

descriptor.label: time derived unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the dimension in which events occur in sequence.

descriptor.label: minute
descriptor.description: A time unit which is equal to 60 seconds.

descriptor.label: day
descriptor.description: A time unit which is equal to 24 hours.

descriptor.label: week
descriptor.description: A time unit which is equal to 7 days.

descriptor.label: century
descriptor.description: A time unit which is equal to 100 years.

descriptor.label: nanosecond

descriptor.label: microsecond
descriptor.description: A time unit which is equal to one millionth of a second or 10^[-6] s.

descriptor.label: length unit

descriptor.label: gram per milliliter

descriptor.label: kilogram per liter

descriptor.label: milligram per milliliter

descriptor.label: gram per deciliter

descriptor.label: cell concentration unit

descriptor.label: katal per cubic meter
descriptor.description: A catalytic (activity) concentration unit which is equal to 1 katal activity of a catalyst in a given volume of one cubic meter.

descriptor.label: volume per unit volume
descriptor.description: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the given volume of the solute in the total volume of the resulting solution.

descriptor.label: milliliter per liter
descriptor.description: A volume per unit volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter of solute in one liter of solution.

descriptor.label: volume percentage
descriptor.description: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the volume of the solute in mL per 100 mL of the resulting solution.

descriptor.label: milliliter per cubic meter
descriptor.description: A volume per unit volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter of solute in one cubic meter of solution.

descriptor.label: colony forming unit per volume
descriptor.description: A concentration unit which a measure of viable bacterial numbers in a given volume.

descriptor.label: colony forming unit per milliliter
descriptor.description: A colony forming unit which a measure of viable bacterial numbers in one milliliter.

descriptor.label: plaque forming unit per volume
descriptor.description: A concentration unit which a measure of plague forming units in a given volume.

descriptor.label: plaque forming unit per milliliter
descriptor.description: A concentration unit which a measure of plague forming units in one milliliter.

descriptor.label: milligram per kilogram
descriptor.description: milligrams per kilo - dose measure

descriptor.label: molar mass unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the mass of a homogeneous substance containing 6.02 x 1023 atoms or molecules.

descriptor.label: kilogram per mole
descriptor.description: A molar mass unit which is equal to one kilogram of mass of one mole of chemical element or chemical compound.

descriptor.label: gram per mole
descriptor.description: A molar mass unit which is equal to one gram of mass of one mole of chemical element or chemical compound.

descriptor.label: molar volume unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the volume of a homogeneous substance containing 6.02 x 1023 atoms or molecules.

descriptor.label: cubic meter per mole
descriptor.description: A molar volume unit which is equal to 1 cubic meter occupied by one mole of a substance in the form of a solid, liquid, or gas.

descriptor.label: cubic centimeter per mole
descriptor.description: A molar volume unit which is equal to 1 cubic centimeter occupied by one mole of a substance in the form of a solid, liquid, or gas.

descriptor.label: rotational frequency unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the number of rotations in a given time.

descriptor.label: one turn per second
descriptor.description: A rotational frequency unit which is equal to 1 complete turn in a period of time that equals to 1 second.

descriptor.label: speed/velocity unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the rate of movement. Speed is measured in the same physical units of measurement as velocity, but does not contain the element of direction that velocity has. Speed is thus the magnitude component of velocity.

descriptor.label: meter per second
descriptor.description: A speed/velocity unit which is equal to the speed of an object traveling 1 meter distance in one second.

descriptor.label: volume unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the amount of space occupied by any substance, whether solid, liquid, or gas.

descriptor.label: cubic meter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to the volume of a cube with edges one meter in length. One cubic meter equals to 1000 liters.

descriptor.label: cubic decimeter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to one thousand of a cubic meter or 10^[-3] m^[3], or to 1 L.

descriptor.label: picoliter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to 10^[-12] L.

descriptor.label: femtoliter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to 10^[-15] L.

descriptor.label: cubic centimeter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a cubic meter or 10^[-9] m^[3], or to 1 ml.

descriptor.label: milliliter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of a liter or 10^[-3] L, or to 1 cubic centimeter.

descriptor.label: liter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of a cubic meter or 10^[-3] m^[3], or to 1 decimeter.

descriptor.label: microliter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter or 10^[-6] L.

descriptor.label: nanoliter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a liter or 10^[-9] L.

descriptor.label: deciliter
descriptor.description: A volume unit which is equal to one tenth of a liter or 10^[-1] L.

descriptor.label: frequency unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the number of repetitive actions in a particular time.

descriptor.label: hertz
descriptor.description: A frequency unit which is equal to 1 complete cycle of a recurring phenomenon in 1 second.

descriptor.label: pressure unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the force applied to a given area.

descriptor.label: pascal
descriptor.description: A pressure unit which is equal to the pressure or stress on a surface caused by a force of 1 newton spread over a surface of 1 m^[2].

descriptor.label: millimetres of mercury
descriptor.description: A unit of pressure equal to the amount of fluid pressure one millimeter deep in mercury at zero degrees centigrade on Earth.

descriptor.label: catalytic activity unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the amount of the action of a catalyst.

descriptor.label: katal
descriptor.description: A catalytic unit activity which is equal to the activity of a catalyst in moles per second, such as the amount of an enzyme needed to transform one mole of substrate per second.

descriptor.label: enzyme unit
descriptor.description: A catalytic unit activity which is equal to the amount of the enzyme that catalyzes the conversion of 1 micro mole of substrate per minute.

descriptor.label: temperature derived unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which represents a standard measurement of temperature in a particular temperature scale.

descriptor.label: degree fahrenheit
descriptor.description: A temperature derived unit which is equal to 5/9ths of a kelvin. Negative 40 degrees Fahrenheit is equal to negative 40 degrees Celsius.

descriptor.label: degree celsius
descriptor.description: A temperature derived unit which is equal to one Kelvin degree. However, they have their zeros at different points. The Centigrade scale has its zero at 273.15 K.

descriptor.label: radiation unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the amount of radiation emitted by a given radiation source as well as the amount of radiation absorbed or deposited in a specific material by a radiation source.

descriptor.label: activity (of a radionuclide) unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the transformation (disintegration) rate of a radioactive substance.

descriptor.label: millicurie
descriptor.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to one thousandth of a curie or 10^[-3] Ci.

descriptor.label: counts per minute
descriptor.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the number of light emissions produced by ionizing radiation in one minute.

descriptor.label: becquerel
descriptor.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second or there is one atom disintegration per second (dps).

descriptor.label: curie
descriptor.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which there are 3.7 x 10^[10] atom disintegration per second (dps).

descriptor.label: microcurie
descriptor.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to one millionth of a curie or 10^[-6] Ci.

descriptor.label: disintegrations per minute
descriptor.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per minute or there is one atom disintegration per minute.

descriptor.label: disintegrations per second
descriptor.description: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second or there is one atom disintegration per second.

descriptor.label: absorbed dose unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the energy imparted by ionizing radiation to unit mass of matter such as tissue.

descriptor.label: rad
descriptor.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to 0.01 gray (Gy).

descriptor.label: microgray
descriptor.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one millionth of a gray or 10^[-6] Gy.

descriptor.label: gray
descriptor.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to the absorption of one joule of radiation energy by one kilogram of matter.

descriptor.label: milligray
descriptor.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one thousandth of a gray or 10^[-3] Gy.

descriptor.label: nanogray
descriptor.description: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one thousandth of a millionth of a gray or 10^[-9] Gy.

descriptor.label: dose equivalent unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the expression of dose in terms of its biological effect.

descriptor.label: sievert
descriptor.description: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to the absorption of one joule of radiation energy by one kilogram of matter.

descriptor.label: nanosievert
descriptor.description: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one thousandth of a millionth of a sievert or 10^[-9] Sv.

descriptor.label: millisievert
descriptor.description: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one thousandth of a sievert or 10^[-3] Sv.

descriptor.label: microsievert
descriptor.description: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one millionth of a sievert or 10^[-6] Sv.

descriptor.label: Roentgen equivalent man
descriptor.description: A dose equivalent unit which when multiplied by hundred is equal to one sievert or 1 Sv. 1 Sv is equal to 100 rem.

descriptor.label: exposure unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the quantity that expresses the ability of radiation to ionize air and thereby create electric charges which can be collected and measured.

descriptor.label: roentgen
descriptor.description: An exposure unit which is equal to the amount of radiation required to liberate positive and negative charges of one electrostatic unit of charge in 1 cm^[3] of air at standard temperature and pressure (STP). This corresponds to the generation of approximately 2.0810^[9] ion pairs.

descriptor.label: effective dose unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the estimate of the stochastic effect that a non-uniform radiation dose has on a human.

descriptor.label: micro curie per milliliter
descriptor.description: from the Broad - Patrick AID min Assay Sheet

descriptor.label: light unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the intensity of light.

descriptor.label: illuminance unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the luminous flux incident on a unit area.

descriptor.label: lux
descriptor.description: An illuminance unit which is equal to the illuminance produced by 1 lumen evenly spread over an area 1 m^[2].

descriptor.label: foot candle
descriptor.description: An illuminance unit which is equal to the illuminance produced by 1 lumen evenly spread over an area 1 foot^[2]. One footcandle is equal to 10.76 lux.

descriptor.label: luminous flux unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the flow of radiant energy.

descriptor.label: lumen
descriptor.description: A luminous flux unit which is equal to the luminous flux emitted into 1 steradian by a point source of 1 candela.

descriptor.label: radiant intensity unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the intensity of electromagnetic radiation.

descriptor.label: watt per steradian
descriptor.description: A radiant intensity unit which is equal to one kilogram meter squared per second cubed per steradian.

descriptor.label: luminance unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the luminous intensity impinging on a given area.

descriptor.label: candela per square meter
descriptor.description: A luminance unit which is equal to a luminous intensity of one candela radiating from a surface whose area is one square meter.

descriptor.label: irradiance unit
descriptor.description: A derived unit which is a standard measure of the power of electromagnetic radiation at a surface, per unit area.

descriptor.label: watt per square meter
descriptor.description: An irradiance unit which is equal to 1 watt of radiant power incident per one square meter surface area.
